data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | **Timeout enforcement** | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **ResetAbort to continue** | Remove entirely |

### Why It Breaks on .NET 6+

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

If you also want an `async` overload (recommended):

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken callerToken = default)
{
    using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(callerToken);
    cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!callerToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Cancellation won't interrupt CPU-bound work** | `Task.Run` only checks the token at *start*. If `work()` is a tight loop, it keeps running after timeout. Pass `CancellationToken` into `work` and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary to convert to `TimeoutException`. Let it propagate otherwise. |
| **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted** | Synchronous `Socket.Receive`, `File.Read`, etc. ignore the token. Use async overloads that accept `CancellationToken`. |

### For truly uncooperative code

If `work()` is third-party code you can't modify to check a token, the **only** safe option on .NET 8 is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort`.

---

### Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` / `ThreadAbortException` / `ResetAbort` remaining
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- ✅ Timeout converted to `TimeoutException` at the boundary
- ✅ Builds cleanly with zero `SYSLIB0006` warnings
